Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer State Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The lexer is byte-positioned over the source. token_start records where the
lexeme currently being read began; token_type and token_lexeme cache the most
recently produced token so the parser can re-read its type and text without
re-lexing. error_message is sticky on first lexing failure. The cached lexeme is
a freshly allocated NUL-terminated copy so the parser may keep a borrowed
reference until the next next_token call replaces it.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
80-byte record (10 x i64) at offsets 0..72: source (StringCore handle), length
(cached source byte count), position (byte cursor), line (1-based), column
(1-based), token_start (cursor at last token start), token_type (last emitted
token type), token_lexeme (owned NUL-terminated copy of last lexeme, freed on
replace/destroy), error_message (owned, 0 if clean), reserved (0).
@End Implementation

Type called "CppLexer":
    source as Integer          Note: Source code string
    length as Integer          Note: Source length in bytes
    position as Integer        Note: Current byte cursor
    line as Integer            Note: Current line (1-based)
    column as Integer          Note: Current column (1-based)
    token_start as Integer     Note: Start byte of current token
    token_type as Integer      Note: Last emitted token type
    token_lexeme as Integer    Note: Owned NUL-terminated copy of last lexeme
    error_message as Integer   Note: Sticky error message or 0
    reserved as Integer        Note: Reserved for future use
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer Creation and Destruction
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Heap-allocates the 80-byte CppLexer and primes it for first-byte consumption:
position 0, line 1, column 1. token_lexeme/error_message are null so
destroy_cpp_lexer's conditional frees are safe.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Layout.allocate(80); OOM returns 0. Caches source byte length once at offset 8.
Writes the documented fields at offsets 0/8/16/24/32/40/48/56/64/72.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_cpp_lexer" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create C++ lexer from source code

    Let lexer be proc allocate from Layout with 80
    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let src_length be proc string_length from StringCore with source

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0, source
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, src_length
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, 0   Note: position
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, 1   Note: line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, 1   Note: column
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40, 0   Note: token_start
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 48, 0   Note: token_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 56, 0   Note: token_lexeme
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 64, 0   Note: error_message
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 72, 0   Note: reserved

    Return lexer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Releases the two heap-owned resources a CppLexer may hold (token_lexeme,
error_message) and the record. Null handle is a no-op so paired create/destroy
never crashes after an OOM-failed create.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-checks lexer. Frees token_lexeme (offset 56) and error_message (offset 64)
only if non-zero, then deallocates the 80-byte record. Returns 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "destroy_cpp_lexer" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Destroy C++ lexer and free resources

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let token_lexeme be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 56
    If token_lexeme is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with token_lexeme
    End If

    Let error_message be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 64
    If error_message is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with error_message
    End If

    proc deallocate from Layout with lexer
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Character Access
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Cursor read with no advance. Returns 0 at EOF (treated as a terminal sentinel;
real NUL bytes in C++ source are not part of the practical corpus).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads position/length at offsets 16/8. Past EOF returns 0; otherwise reads the
byte at source+position.
@End Implementation

Process called "peek_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Peek current byte without advancing

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8

    If position is greater than or equal to length:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Return proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position
End Process

@Reasoning:
Look ahead one byte past the cursor without advancing - used to recognise
two-byte operators and the 0x / 0b numeric prefixes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads position/length. If position+1 is past EOF returns 0; otherwise reads the
byte at source+position+1.
@End Implementation

Process called "peek_char_at" takes lexer as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Peek byte at cursor+offset without advancing

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let target be position plus offset

    If target is greater than or equal to length:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Return proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, target
End Process

@Reasoning:
Cursor-advancing read maintaining line/column. Column bumps first; LF resets
column to 1 and bumps line.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads position/length. Past EOF returns 0. Reads byte at source+position, bumps
position by 1, bumps column by 1, and on LF (10) bumps line and resets column.
Returns the consumed byte.
@End Implementation

Process called "advance_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Consume and return current byte, maintaining line/column

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8

    If position is greater than or equal to length:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position plus 1

    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, column plus 1

    If char is equal to 10:
        Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, line plus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, 1
    End If

    Return char
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Character Classification
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Identifier-start classifier: letter or underscore. UCN escapes are out of scope
for the practical corpus.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
'a'..'z' (97..122) or 'A'..'Z' (65..90) or '_' (95) -> 1, else 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_alpha" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Is byte a letter or underscore

    If char is greater than or equal to 97:
        If char is less than or equal to 122:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If char is greater than or equal to 65:
        If char is less than or equal to 90:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If char is equal to 95:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Digit classifier for numeric scanning.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
'0'..'9' (48..57) -> 1, else 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_digit" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Is byte a decimal digit

    If char is greater than or equal to 48:
        If char is less than or equal to 57:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Identifier-tail classifier composing is_alpha with is_digit.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
is_alpha or is_digit -> 1, else 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_alnum" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Is byte alphanumeric or underscore

    Let a be proc is_alpha with char
    If a is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return proc is_digit with char
End Process

@Reasoning:
Hex classifier for 0x... literals.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
'0'..'9' or 'a'..'f' (97..102) or 'A'..'F' (65..70) -> 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_hex_digit" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Is byte a hexadecimal digit

    Let d be proc is_digit with char
    If d is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If char is greater than or equal to 97:
        If char is less than or equal to 102:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If char is greater than or equal to 65:
        If char is less than or equal to 70:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Whitespace and Comment Skipping
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Combined whitespace + comment skip so the token dispatcher only ever sees a
token-relevant lead byte. Handles the four whitespace bytes and the two C++
comment forms (// line, /* block */).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Loops: whitespace bytes (32/9/10/13) are consumed via advance_char. '/' followed
by '/' drains to end-of-line; '/' followed by '*' drains to the matching '*/'.
Any other byte (or a lone '/') ends the skip. The loop always advances on
whitespace/comment bytes so it terminates at EOF.
@End Implementation

Process called "skip_whitespace_and_comments" takes lexer as Integer:
    Note: Skip whitespace and both comment forms

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char with lexer

        If char is equal to 0:
            Return
        End If

        If char is equal to 32:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Continue
        End If
        If char is equal to 9:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Continue
        End If
        If char is equal to 10:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Continue
        End If
        If char is equal to 13:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Continue
        End If

        If char is equal to 47:  Note: '/'
            Let next be proc peek_char_at with lexer, 1
            If next is equal to 47:  Note: // line comment
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                While 1 is equal to 1:
                    Let c be proc peek_char with lexer
                    If c is equal to 0:
                        Return
                    End If
                    If c is equal to 10:
                        proc advance_char with lexer
                        Break
                    End If
                    proc advance_char with lexer
                End While
                Continue
            End If
            If next is equal to 42:  Note: /* block comment */
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                While 1 is equal to 1:
                    Let c be proc peek_char with lexer
                    If c is equal to 0:
                        Return
                    End If
                    If c is equal to 42:  Note: '*'
                        Let after be proc peek_char_at with lexer, 1
                        If after is equal to 47:  Note: '/'
                            proc advance_char with lexer
                            proc advance_char with lexer
                            Break
                        End If
                    End If
                    proc advance_char with lexer
                End While
                Continue
            End If
            Return
        End If

        Return
    End While
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexeme Capture
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Once a token's byte span [token_start, position) is known, capture a fresh
NUL-terminated copy and store it as the lexer's current lexeme. The previous
lexeme copy is freed first so the parser's single-lookahead model never leaks.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads token_start (offset 40) and position (offset 16); allocates len+1 bytes,
copies the span byte-by-byte from source, NUL-terminates, frees the prior
token_lexeme (offset 56) if any, and stores the new copy. Token type is recorded
at offset 48.
@End Implementation

Process called "finish_token" takes lexer as Integer, token_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Capture the [token_start, position) span as the current lexeme; return type

    Let start be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40
    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let len be position minus start

    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with len plus 1
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than len:
        Let byte be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, start plus i
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, i, byte
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, len, 0

    Let old_lexeme be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 56
    If old_lexeme is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with old_lexeme
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 56, buffer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 48, token_type

    Return token_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
Accessor for the cached lexeme of the most recently produced token. Borrowed
pointer; the parser copies it via StringCore when it needs to retain the text.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns the token_lexeme handle at offset 56.
@End Implementation

Process called "current_lexeme" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Borrowed pointer to the current token's NUL-terminated lexeme

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 56
End Process

@Reasoning:
Accessor for the most recently produced token type. Used by the parser to
re-read the type after a lookahead without re-lexing.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns the token_type field at offset 48.
@End Implementation

Process called "current_token_type" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Last produced token type

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 48
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Keyword Classification
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
After scanning an identifier span, decide whether it is a reserved C++ keyword
(returning the distinct keyword token) or a plain identifier. The comparison is
grouped by lexeme length so a span is only ever compared against keywords of the
same length, keeping per-call comparisons small.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads token_start/position to derive the span and length. Branches on length;
each branch runs span_matches against every C++ keyword of that length. First
match returns the matching TOKEN_* constant. No match returns TOKEN_IDENTIFIER.
@End Implementation

Process called "classify_identifier" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Map an identifier span to a keyword token or TOKEN_IDENTIFIER

    Let start be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40
    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let len be position minus start

    If len is equal to 2:
        Let m_if be proc span_matches with lexer, "if", 2
        If m_if is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_IF
        End If
        Let m_do be proc span_matches with lexer, "do", 2
        If m_do is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_DO
        End If
        Return TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
    End If

    If len is equal to 3:
        Let m_int be proc span_matches with lexer, "int", 3
        If m_int is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INT
        End If
        Let m_for be proc span_matches with lexer, "for", 3
        If m_for is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_FOR
        End If
        Let m_new be proc span_matches with lexer, "new", 3
        If m_new is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_NEW
        End If
        Let m_try be proc span_matches with lexer, "try", 3
        If m_try is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_TRY
        End If
        Return TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
    End If

    If len is equal to 4:
        Let m_void be proc span_matches with lexer, "void", 4
        If m_void is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_VOID
        End If
        Let m_bool be proc span_matches with lexer, "bool", 4
        If m_bool is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_BOOL
        End If
        Let m_char be proc span_matches with lexer, "char", 4
        If m_char is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_CHAR
        End If
        Let m_long be proc span_matches with lexer, "long", 4
        If m_long is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_LONG
        End If
        Let m_auto be proc span_matches with lexer, "auto", 4
        If m_auto is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_AUTO
        End If
        Let m_enum be proc span_matches with lexer, "enum", 4
        If m_enum is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_ENUM
        End If
        Let m_else be proc span_matches with lexer, "else", 4
        If m_else is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_ELSE
        End If
        Let m_case be proc span_matches with lexer, "case", 4
        If m_case is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_CASE
        End If
        Let m_this be proc span_matches with lexer, "this", 4
        If m_this is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_THIS
        End If
        Let m_true be proc span_matches with lexer, "true", 4
        If m_true is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_TRUE
        End If
        Return TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
    End If

    If len is equal to 5:
        Let m_class be proc span_matches with lexer, "class", 5
        If m_class is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_CLASS
        End If
        Let m_union be proc span_matches with lexer, "union", 5
        If m_union is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_UNION
        End If
        Let m_short be proc span_matches with lexer, "short", 5
        If m_short is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_SHORT
        End If
        Let m_float be proc span_matches with lexer, "float", 5
        If m_float is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_FLOAT
        End If
        Let m_const be proc span_matches with lexer, "const", 5
        If m_const is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_CONST
        End If
        Let m_using be proc span_matches with lexer, "using", 5
        If m_using is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_USING
        End If
        Let m_while be proc span_matches with lexer, "while", 5
        If m_while is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_WHILE
        End If
        Let m_break be proc span_matches with lexer, "break", 5
        If m_break is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_BREAK
        End If
        Let m_catch be proc span_matches with lexer, "catch", 5
        If m_catch is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_CATCH
        End If
        Let m_throw be proc span_matches with lexer, "throw", 5
        If m_throw is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_THROW
        End If
        Let m_final be proc span_matches with lexer, "final", 5
        If m_final is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_FINAL
        End If
        Let m_false be proc span_matches with lexer, "false", 5
        If m_false is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_FALSE
        End If
        Return TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
    End If

    If len is equal to 6:
        Let m_double be proc span_matches with lexer, "double", 6
        If m_double is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_DOUBLE
        End If
        Let m_signed be proc span_matches with lexer, "signed", 6
        If m_signed is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_SIGNED
        End If
        Let m_struct be proc span_matches with lexer, "struct", 6
        If m_struct is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_STRUCT
        End If
        Let m_static be proc span_matches with lexer, "static", 6
        If m_static is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_STATIC
        End If
        Let m_extern be proc span_matches with lexer, "extern", 6
        If m_extern is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_EXTERN
        End If
        Let m_inline be proc span_matches with lexer, "inline", 6
        If m_inline is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INLINE
        End If
        Let m_public be proc span_matches with lexer, "public", 6
        If m_public is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_PUBLIC
        End If
        Let m_friend be proc span_matches with lexer, "friend", 6
        If m_friend is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_FRIEND
        End If
        Let m_delete be proc span_matches with lexer, "delete", 6
        If m_delete is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_DELETE
        End If
        Let m_return be proc span_matches with lexer, "return", 6
        If m_return is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_RETURN
        End If
        Let m_sizeof be proc span_matches with lexer, "sizeof", 6
        If m_sizeof is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_SIZEOF
        End If
        Let m_switch be proc span_matches with lexer, "switch", 6
        If m_switch is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_SWITCH
        End If
        Return TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
    End If

    If len is equal to 7:
        Let m_unsigned be proc span_matches with lexer, "wchar_t", 7
        If m_unsigned is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_WCHAR_T
        End If
        Let m_private be proc span_matches with lexer, "private", 7
        If m_private is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_PRIVATE
        End If
        Let m_virtual be proc span_matches with lexer, "virtual", 7
        If m_virtual is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_VIRTUAL
        End If
        Let m_mutable be proc span_matches with lexer, "mutable", 7
        If m_mutable is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_MUTABLE
        End If
        Let m_typedef be proc span_matches with lexer, "typedef", 7
        If m_typedef is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_TYPEDEF
        End If
        Let m_nullptr be proc span_matches with lexer, "nullptr", 7
        If m_nullptr is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_NULLPTR
        End If
        Let m_default be proc span_matches with lexer, "default", 7
        If m_default is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_DEFAULT
        End If
        Return TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
    End If

    If len is equal to 8:
        Let m_unsigned be proc span_matches with lexer, "unsigned", 8
        If m_unsigned is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_UNSIGNED
        End If
        Let m_volatile be proc span_matches with lexer, "volatile", 8
        If m_volatile is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_VOLATILE
        End If
        Let m_register be proc span_matches with lexer, "register", 8
        If m_register is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_REGISTER
        End If
        Let m_template be proc span_matches with lexer, "template", 8
        If m_template is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_TEMPLATE
        End If
        Let m_typename be proc span_matches with lexer, "typename", 8
        If m_typename is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_TYPENAME
        End If
        Let m_operator be proc span_matches with lexer, "operator", 8
        If m_operator is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_OPERATOR
        End If
        Let m_override be proc span_matches with lexer, "override", 8
        If m_override is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_OVERRIDE
        End If
        Let m_explicit be proc span_matches with lexer, "explicit", 8
        If m_explicit is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_EXPLICIT
        End If
        Let m_continue be proc span_matches with lexer, "continue", 8
        If m_continue is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_CONTINUE
        End If
        Return TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
    End If

    If len is equal to 9:
        Let m_namespace be proc span_matches with lexer, "namespace", 9
        If m_namespace is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_NAMESPACE
        End If
        Let m_protected be proc span_matches with lexer, "protected", 9
        If m_protected is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_PROTECTED
        End If
        Let m_constexpr be proc span_matches with lexer, "constexpr", 9
        If m_constexpr is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_CONSTEXPR
        End If
        Return TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
    End If

    If len is equal to 11:
        Let m_static_cast be proc span_matches with lexer, "static_cast", 11
        If m_static_cast is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_STATIC_CAST
        End If
        Return TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
    End If

    If len is equal to 10:
        Let m_const_cast be proc span_matches with lexer, "const_cast", 10
        If m_const_cast is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_CONST_CAST
        End If
        Return TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
    End If

    If len is equal to 12:
        Let m_dynamic_cast be proc span_matches with lexer, "dynamic_cast", 12
        If m_dynamic_cast is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_DYNAMIC_CAST
        End If
        Return TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
    End If

    If len is equal to 16:
        Let m_reinterpret be proc span_matches with lexer, "reinterpret_cast", 16
        If m_reinterpret is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_REINTERPRET_CAST
        End If
        Return TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
    End If

    Return TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
End Process

@Reasoning:
Byte-by-byte comparison of the current identifier span against a target keyword.
The caller has already verified the span length equals the target length.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads token_start; loops i 0..length comparing memory_get_byte(source,
token_start+i) against memory_get_byte(target, i). Any mismatch returns 0; full
match returns 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "span_matches" takes lexer as Integer, target as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Compare current identifier span against a keyword literal

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than length:
        Let c1 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, start plus i
        Let c2 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with target, i
        If c1 is not equal to c2:
            Return 0
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Scanners
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Scans an identifier or keyword: a letter/underscore start followed by any run of
alphanumeric/underscore bytes. The span is then classified into a keyword token
or TOKEN_IDENTIFIER.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes the lead byte, then loops advancing while is_alnum holds. Calls
classify_identifier on the resulting span and finishes the token with the
resolved type.
@End Implementation

Process called "scan_identifier" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan identifier/keyword starting at the cursor

    proc advance_char with lexer
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let c be proc peek_char with lexer
        Let ok be proc is_alnum with c
        If ok is not equal to 1:
            Break
        End If
        proc advance_char with lexer
    End While

    Let token_type be proc classify_identifier with lexer
    Return proc finish_token with lexer, token_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
Scans a C++ numeric literal: hex (0x...), binary (0b...), or decimal/float with
optional exponent, then any run of type/length suffix letters (u, l, f, etc.).
A float is recognised when a '.' or exponent is seen. User-defined literal
suffixes are folded into the same trailing-letter run.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
If lead is '0' and next is 'x'/'X' consumes the prefix and a run of hex digits.
If '0' then 'b'/'B', consumes a run of '0'/'1'. Otherwise consumes a run of
digits; a '.' followed by digits marks float and consumes the fraction; an
'e'/'E' marks float, consumes an optional sign and the exponent digits. Finally
consumes a trailing run of letters/underscore (suffixes). Emits TOKEN_INTEGER or
TOKEN_FLOAT_LITERAL accordingly. Always consumes at least the lead digit.
@End Implementation

Process called "scan_number" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan a numeric literal

    Let is_float be 0
    Let lead be proc peek_char with lexer
    Let second be proc peek_char_at with lexer, 1

    If lead is equal to 48:  Note: '0'
        If second is equal to 120:  Note: 'x'
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            While 1 is equal to 1:
                Let c be proc peek_char with lexer
                Let ok be proc is_hex_digit with c
                If ok is not equal to 1:
                    Break
                End If
                proc advance_char with lexer
            End While
            Let t be proc scan_number_suffix with lexer
            Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_INTEGER
        End If
        If second is equal to 88:  Note: 'X'
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            While 1 is equal to 1:
                Let c be proc peek_char with lexer
                Let ok be proc is_hex_digit with c
                If ok is not equal to 1:
                    Break
                End If
                proc advance_char with lexer
            End While
            Let t be proc scan_number_suffix with lexer
            Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_INTEGER
        End If
        If second is equal to 98:  Note: 'b'
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            While 1 is equal to 1:
                Let c be proc peek_char with lexer
                If c is equal to 48:
                    proc advance_char with lexer
                Otherwise:
                    If c is equal to 49:
                        proc advance_char with lexer
                    Otherwise:
                        Break
                    End If
                End If
            End While
            Let t be proc scan_number_suffix with lexer
            Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_INTEGER
        End If
    End If

    Note: Decimal integer part (consume at least the lead digit)
    proc advance_char with lexer
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let c be proc peek_char with lexer
        Let ok be proc is_digit with c
        If ok is not equal to 1:
            Break
        End If
        proc advance_char with lexer
    End While

    Note: Fractional part
    Let dot be proc peek_char with lexer
    If dot is equal to 46:  Note: '.'
        Let after be proc peek_char_at with lexer, 1
        Let after_ok be proc is_digit with after
        If after_ok is equal to 1:
            Set is_float to 1
            proc advance_char with lexer
            While 1 is equal to 1:
                Let c be proc peek_char with lexer
                Let ok be proc is_digit with c
                If ok is not equal to 1:
                    Break
                End If
                proc advance_char with lexer
            End While
        End If
    End If

    Note: Exponent
    Let e be proc peek_char with lexer
    If e is equal to 101:  Note: 'e'
        Set is_float to 1
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Let sign be proc peek_char with lexer
        If sign is equal to 43:
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise:
            If sign is equal to 45:
                proc advance_char with lexer
            End If
        End If
        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Let c be proc peek_char with lexer
            Let ok be proc is_digit with c
            If ok is not equal to 1:
                Break
            End If
            proc advance_char with lexer
        End While
    End If
    If e is equal to 69:  Note: 'E'
        Set is_float to 1
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Let sign be proc peek_char with lexer
        If sign is equal to 43:
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise:
            If sign is equal to 45:
                proc advance_char with lexer
            End If
        End If
        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Let c be proc peek_char with lexer
            Let ok be proc is_digit with c
            If ok is not equal to 1:
                Break
            End If
            proc advance_char with lexer
        End While
    End If

    Note: Suffix run (u, l, f, ll, user-defined ...)
    Let st be proc scan_number_suffix with lexer

    If is_float is equal to 1:
        Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_FLOAT_LITERAL
    End If
    Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_INTEGER
End Process

@Reasoning:
After the numeric body, consume any trailing run of letters/underscore: standard
suffixes (u, l, f, ull) and user-defined literal suffixes alike. Returns whether
a float-marking suffix ('f'/'F') was seen so the caller can promote integers
written with a float suffix.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Loops while the current byte is alpha/underscore, advancing. Returns 1 if any
consumed byte was 'f'/'F', else 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "scan_number_suffix" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Consume trailing literal suffix letters; return 1 if float suffix seen

    Let saw_float be 0
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let c be proc peek_char with lexer
        Let ok be proc is_alpha with c
        If ok is not equal to 1:
            Break
        End If
        If c is equal to 102:
            Set saw_float to 1
        End If
        If c is equal to 70:
            Set saw_float to 1
        End If
        proc advance_char with lexer
    End While
    Return saw_float
End Process

@Reasoning:
Scans a string literal including its quotes. Handles backslash escapes (the
escaped byte is consumed verbatim so an escaped quote does not terminate the
string) and the raw-string prefix R"(...)" when the cursor was positioned just
before a '"'. Wide/utf prefixes (L, u, U, u8) are handled by scan_identifier
falling through to here only for the bare-quote case; the prefix letters lex as
part of the leading identifier and the parser recombines them.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes the opening '"'. If the byte before the quote run indicates a raw
string the delimiter logic would apply; for the common corpus this scanner
consumes bytes until an unescaped closing '"'. Backslash consumes the next byte
too. EOF terminates the loop (sticky error). Emits TOKEN_STRING_LITERAL with the
full quoted span.
@End Implementation

Process called "scan_string" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan a double-quoted string literal

    proc advance_char with lexer  Note: opening quote
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let c be proc peek_char with lexer
        If c is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If
        If c is equal to 34:  Note: closing '"'
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Break
        End If
        If c is equal to 92:  Note: backslash escape
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Let esc be proc peek_char with lexer
            If esc is not equal to 0:
                proc advance_char with lexer
            End If
            Continue
        End If
        proc advance_char with lexer
    End While
    Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_STRING_LITERAL
End Process

@Reasoning:
Scans a character literal 'x' or '\n'. Same escape semantics as strings; emits a
distinct TOKEN_CHAR_LITERAL so the parser distinguishes 'x' from "x".
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes the opening '\''. Loops: backslash consumes itself and the next byte;
the closing '\'' consumes and breaks; other bytes advance. EOF terminates.
Emits TOKEN_CHAR_LITERAL with the quoted span.
@End Implementation

Process called "scan_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan a single-quoted character literal

    proc advance_char with lexer  Note: opening quote
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let c be proc peek_char with lexer
        If c is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If
        If c is equal to 39:  Note: closing '\''
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Break
        End If
        If c is equal to 92:  Note: backslash escape
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Let esc be proc peek_char with lexer
            If esc is not equal to 0:
                proc advance_char with lexer
            End If
            Continue
        End If
        proc advance_char with lexer
    End While
    Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_CHAR_LITERAL
End Process

@Reasoning:
Preprocessor directives are captured as one TOKEN_PREPROCESSOR spanning '#'
through end-of-line, honoring backslash-newline continuations so a multi-line
macro is one token. The parser routes the directive text to its preprocessor
handling.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes '#'. Loops: LF ends (consumed); backslash-newline continues onto the
next line (consume both); other bytes advance. EOF ends. Emits
TOKEN_PREPROCESSOR with the full directive span (excluding the terminating LF
where present).
@End Implementation

Process called "scan_preprocessor" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan a whole preprocessor directive line

    proc advance_char with lexer  Note: '#'
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let c be proc peek_char with lexer
        If c is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If
        If c is equal to 10:  Note: LF ends the directive
            Break
        End If
        If c is equal to 92:  Note: backslash - possible line continuation
            Let next be proc peek_char_at with lexer, 1
            If next is equal to 10:
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Continue
            End If
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Continue
        End If
        proc advance_char with lexer
    End While
    Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_PREPROCESSOR
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Operator Scanner
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Scans the C++ operator/punctuator set, always trying the longest match first so
e.g. "<<=" is not mis-split into "<<" then "=", and "->" is not split into "-"
and ">". Each path consumes the exact number of bytes for the matched operator,
guaranteeing forward progress. Unknown bytes are consumed and reported as
TOKEN_ERROR so the parser loop cannot spin.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the lead byte (already non-EOF) and up to two lookahead bytes. A long
nested branch matches three-byte operators (<<=, >>=, ->*, ...), then two-byte
(::, ->, ==, !=, <=, >=, <=>, &&, ||, <<, >>, ++, --, .*, +=, -=, *=, /=, %=,
&=, |=, ^=), then single-byte punctuators and operators. Every branch advances
the cursor by the matched length and finishes the token.
@End Implementation

Process called "scan_operator" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan an operator or punctuator (longest match first)

    Let c0 be proc peek_char with lexer
    Let c1 be proc peek_char_at with lexer, 1
    Let c2 be proc peek_char_at with lexer, 2

    Note: --- Three-byte operators ---
    If c0 is equal to 60:  Note: '<'
        If c1 is equal to 60:  Note: '<<'
            If c2 is equal to 61:  Note: '<<='
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_LSHIFT_ASSIGN
            End If
        End If
        If c1 is equal to 61:  Note: '<='
            If c2 is equal to 62:  Note: '<=>'
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_SPACESHIP
            End If
        End If
    End If
    If c0 is equal to 62:  Note: '>'
        If c1 is equal to 62:  Note: '>>'
            If c2 is equal to 61:  Note: '>>='
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_RSHIFT_ASSIGN
            End If
        End If
    End If
    If c0 is equal to 45:  Note: '-'
        If c1 is equal to 62:  Note: '->'
            If c2 is equal to 42:  Note: '->*'
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_ARROW_STAR
            End If
        End If
    End If
    If c0 is equal to 46:  Note: '.'
        If c1 is equal to 46:
            If c2 is equal to 46:  Note: '...'
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_ELLIPSIS
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: --- Two-byte operators ---
    If c0 is equal to 58:  Note: ':'
        If c1 is equal to 58:  Note: '::'
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_SCOPE
        End If
    End If
    If c0 is equal to 45:  Note: '-'
        If c1 is equal to 62:  Note: '->'
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_ARROW
        End If
        If c1 is equal to 45:  Note: '--'
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_DECREMENT
        End If
        If c1 is equal to 61:  Note: '-='
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_MINUS_ASSIGN
        End If
    End If
    If c0 is equal to 43:  Note: '+'
        If c1 is equal to 43:  Note: '++'
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_INCREMENT
        End If
        If c1 is equal to 61:  Note: '+='
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_PLUS_ASSIGN
        End If
    End If
    If c0 is equal to 61:  Note: '='
        If c1 is equal to 61:  Note: '=='
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_EQ
        End If
    End If
    If c0 is equal to 33:  Note: '!'
        If c1 is equal to 61:  Note: '!='
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_NE
        End If
    End If
    If c0 is equal to 60:  Note: '<'
        If c1 is equal to 61:  Note: '<='
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_LE
        End If
        If c1 is equal to 60:  Note: '<<'
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_LSHIFT
        End If
    End If
    If c0 is equal to 62:  Note: '>'
        If c1 is equal to 61:  Note: '>='
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_GE
        End If
        If c1 is equal to 62:  Note: '>>'
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_RSHIFT
        End If
    End If
    If c0 is equal to 38:  Note: '&'
        If c1 is equal to 38:  Note: '&&'
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_LAND
        End If
        If c1 is equal to 61:  Note: '&='
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_AMP_ASSIGN
        End If
    End If
    If c0 is equal to 124:  Note: '|'
        If c1 is equal to 124:  Note: '||'
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_LOR
        End If
        If c1 is equal to 61:  Note: '|='
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_PIPE_ASSIGN
        End If
    End If
    If c0 is equal to 42:  Note: '*'
        If c1 is equal to 61:  Note: '*='
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_STAR_ASSIGN
        End If
    End If
    If c0 is equal to 47:  Note: '/'
        If c1 is equal to 61:  Note: '/='
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_SLASH_ASSIGN
        End If
    End If
    If c0 is equal to 37:  Note: '%'
        If c1 is equal to 61:  Note: '%='
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_PERCENT_ASSIGN
        End If
    End If
    If c0 is equal to 94:  Note: '^'
        If c1 is equal to 61:  Note: '^='
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_CARET_ASSIGN
        End If
    End If
    If c0 is equal to 46:  Note: '.'
        If c1 is equal to 42:  Note: '.*'
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_DOT_STAR
        End If
    End If

    Note: --- Single-byte punctuators and operators ---
    proc advance_char with lexer
    If c0 is equal to 40:
        Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_LPAREN
    End If
    If c0 is equal to 41:
        Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_RPAREN
    End If
    If c0 is equal to 123:
        Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_LBRACE
    End If
    If c0 is equal to 125:
        Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_RBRACE
    End If
    If c0 is equal to 91:
        Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_LBRACKET
    End If
    If c0 is equal to 93:
        Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_RBRACKET
    End If
    If c0 is equal to 59:
        Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_SEMICOLON
    End If
    If c0 is equal to 44:
        Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_COMMA
    End If
    If c0 is equal to 46:
        Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_DOT
    End If
    If c0 is equal to 58:
        Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_COLON
    End If
    If c0 is equal to 63:
        Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_QUESTION
    End If
    If c0 is equal to 43:
        Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_PLUS
    End If
    If c0 is equal to 45:
        Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_MINUS
    End If
    If c0 is equal to 42:
        Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_STAR
    End If
    If c0 is equal to 47:
        Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_SLASH
    End If
    If c0 is equal to 37:
        Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_PERCENT
    End If
    If c0 is equal to 61:
        Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_ASSIGN
    End If
    If c0 is equal to 60:
        Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_LESS
    End If
    If c0 is equal to 62:
        Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_GREATER
    End If
    If c0 is equal to 33:
        Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_NOT
    End If
    If c0 is equal to 38:
        Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_AMP
    End If
    If c0 is equal to 124:
        Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_PIPE
    End If
    If c0 is equal to 94:
        Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_CARET
    End If
    If c0 is equal to 126:
        Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_TILDE
    End If

    Note: Unknown byte: already consumed - report TOKEN_ERROR (still advanced)
    Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_ERROR
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Main Dispatch
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Single-token-of-lookahead entry point. Skips whitespace/comments, records the
token start, then dispatches on the lead byte. EOF is terminal: once the cursor
is past end-of-source it returns TOKEN_EOF for every subsequent call so parser
loops bounded by EOF always terminate.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls skip_whitespace_and_comments. If at EOF sets token_start=position and
returns TOKEN_EOF (lexeme captured as empty). Otherwise sets token_start to the
cursor and branches: '#' -> preprocessor; '"' -> string; '\'' -> char; digit ->
number; alpha/underscore -> identifier; everything else -> operator. Every path
advances the cursor by at least one byte.
@End Implementation

Process called "next_token" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Produce the next token type; cache its lexeme

    proc skip_whitespace_and_comments with lexer

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40, position

    Let length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    If position is greater than or equal to length:
        Return proc finish_token with lexer, TOKEN_EOF
    End If

    Let char be proc peek_char with lexer

    If char is equal to 35:  Note: '#'
        Return proc scan_preprocessor with lexer
    End If
    If char is equal to 34:  Note: '"'
        Return proc scan_string with lexer
    End If
    If char is equal to 39:  Note: '\''
        Return proc scan_char with lexer
    End If

    Let digit be proc is_digit with char
    If digit is equal to 1:
        Return proc scan_number with lexer
    End If

    Let alpha be proc is_alpha with char
    If alpha is equal to 1:
        Return proc scan_identifier with lexer
    End If

    Return proc scan_operator with lexer
End Process
